        "description": "(2021-2022)\nI led DeepMind's flagship work on citing sources with generative language models, GopherCite. I also worked directly on many of DeepMind’s major LLM projects including Gopher, RETRO, and Flamingo.\nhttps://arxiv.org/abs/2203.11147\nhttps://arxiv.org/abs/2112.11446\nhttps://arxiv.org/abs/2112.04426\n\n(2020 - 2021)\nPaved the way for DeepMind's multimodal LMs:\n- Proposed to feed image representations to a frozen autoregressive LM [Frozen]\n- Collaborated on adopting this approach in the Flamingo project.\nhttps://arxiv.org/abs/2106.13884\nhttps://arxiv.org/abs/2204.14198\n\n(2019 - 2020)\nWrote DeepMind's first transformer sharding code and conducted early LLM research:\n- Concurrently invented something similar to the megatron approach\n- Hacked around jax limitations to produce the first multi-host sharded models\n- Trained DeepMind's first multi-billion parameter transformer LM, focused on question-answering.\n- My implementation was forked to form the basis of the Gopher codebase\n\nI also dabbled in forward-mode learning rules for RNNs during this period [Sparse RTRL].\nhttps://arxiv.org/abs/2006.07232\n\n(2018 - 2020)\nDeveloped SOTA autoregressive image models:\n- Collaborated with Charlie Nash on DCTransformer, directly modelling JPEG-like image formats\n- Subscale Pixel Networks, one of the earliest memory-efficient long-context transformers\nhttps://arxiv.org/abs/2103.03841\nhttps://arxiv.org/abs/1812.01608\n\n(2015 - 2018)\nBefore that, I spent a number of years as the padawan of Alex Graves, working on wide-ranging research topics involving latent variable models [Associative Compression Networks], bayesian NNs [NoisyNet], reinforcement learning [unpublished], memory architectures [unpublished], and active learning [Automatic Curriculum Learning]. Became Alex's PhD student with a focus on unsupervised learning motivated by ideas from information theory and data compression.\nhttps://arxiv.org/abs/1804.02476\nhttps://arxiv.org/abs/1704.03003\nhttps://arxiv.org/abs/1706.10295",
